article.headline: Wyoming 64, Princeton 59 (2 OT)
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Steve Leven was lured to Wyoming to bolster the team's outside shooting. In his first two games as a Cowboy, he's done just that. After sinking 3 of 5 from the arc in the opener against Alcorn State, the Australian sharpshooter was 4 of 6 from 3-point land in Wyoming's 64-59 double-overtime victory against Princeton on Monday. He scored a game-high 29 points, grabbed eight rebounds and netted four free throws down the stretch of the final overtime to clinch it for the Cowboys (2-0). "I just tried to get it going early," he said. Leven sat out 1½ seasons after leaving Auburn midway through his freshman year and is beginning to shake off the rust. "I'm just out there having fun," he said. "My hardest game of the season was my first exhibition game." Despite his offensive prowess, Leven credited the Cowboys' defense with the win. "We did a good job of not letting them get second shots," Leven said. "We focused on sending four to the glass. That was probably the key." Wyoming won the rebound battle 38-30, with the Cowboys' Alex Dunn snaring a game-best 15. UW held Princeton to six offensive boards while grabbing 11. The Cowboys won despite being outshot 40 percent to 34 percent. "To hold them to 40 is pretty darn good," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said. "They shoot in the 60s when they're really rolling." McClain said his team also did a good job with clock management. Wyoming never trailed in the second extra frame after missing last-second shots at the end of regulation and the first overtime. Jay Straight added 15 points for UW and Dunn had 13 points. Princeton (1-2) was led by Will Venable with 17, while Noah Savage added 12 and Judson Wallace 11. Straight missed a short banker in the final 10 seconds of regulation, and although the Cowboys got the ball back, the Tigers forced a turnover just before the buzzer. In the first overtime, Scott Greenman sank a 3-pointer to put Princeton up 57-55, but Dunn answered with two foul shots at the 1:04 mark. However, he missed a close attempt just before the buzzer, forcing a second overtime. Straight hit 3 of 4 free throws in the first 1:44 of the final overtime, giving Wyoming a 60-57 lead, and Leven sealed it with four free throws in the final 2:41. A basket by Jerry Webb put the Cowboys ahead 43-41 with 6:51 left in the second half and Wyoming held the lead until Wallace tied it at 49 on a free throw with 42 seconds remaining. Wyoming opened its widest lead, 31-25, after a field goal by Straight with 17:41 left, but Princeton fought back to go up 36-35 on consecutive 3-point shots by Savage and Venable. The Tigers led 17-10 on a basket by Wallace with 7:05 left in the opening half, but Wyoming, sparked by a pair of 3-pointers from Leven, went on a 15-3 run to go up 25-20 at the 1:13 mark before halftime. The Cowboys led 25-22 at the half.
